---
import Base from '~/layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="You're on the list — hookd"
  description="Your spot on the hookd waitlist is confirmed. We'll be in touch."
>
  <main id="main" class="w-full px-6 md:px-12 lg:px-16 py-section">
    <div class="max-w-prose mx-auto space-y-8">
      <p class="font-mono text-sm text-ink-muted tracking-wide text-center">hookd · from OpsKern</p>

      <h1 class="font-display font-bold text-4xl tracking-tight text-ink text-center">
        You're on the list
      </h1>

      <div
        class="border border-surface-raised rounded-lg p-6 space-y-4 text-ink-muted text-base leading-relaxed"
      >
        <p>Hey,</p>

        <p>Thanks for joining the hookd waitlist.</p>

        <p>
          Here's what you're signing up for: hookd sits between your keyboard and every AI tool on
          your machine. Before Claude Code, Cursor, or Copilot can send a prompt, hookd reads it,
          classifies it against your policy, and decides whether to redact, block, or let it
          through. The decision happens locally — no cloud hop, no latency tax.
        </p>

        <p>
          The problem it solves: most AI policy failures happen at the prompt layer, not the model
          layer. Your model doesn't know your IP is proprietary. hookd does.
        </p>

        <p>
          We're opening early access in batches. You'll get an email when your spot is ready — no
          action needed until then.
        </p>

        <p class="pt-2">
          — Will<br />
          <span class="font-mono text-sm text-ink-subtle">OpsKern</span>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="text-ink-subtle text-sm text-center">
        Questions? Write to
        <a href="mailto:hello@opskernel.io" class="text-accent underline">hello@opskernel.io</a>.
      </p>

      <p class="font-mono text-xs text-ink-subtle tracking-wide text-center">
        <a href="/" class="hover:text-accent">← hookd home</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
